# A-LEMS Distributed Orchestration — Master Design Document

**Date:** 2026-03-27  
**Status:** Approved design, ready to implement  
**Scope:** Multi-host execution, PostgreSQL sync, dual-mode UI  
**Constraint:** Zero breaking changes to existing pipeline or schema queries

---

## 0. Ground rules (never violate)

| Rule | Detail |
|------|--------|
| Do NOT rename any existing column | hw_id, exp_id, run_id stay exactly as-is |
| Do NOT touch existing tables destructively | Only ADD columns, never modify/drop |
| Do NOT rewrite the execution pipeline | `test_harness` command is called identically |
| Do NOT make Streamlit depend on server | Local mode must work fully offline |
| Measurement integrity > everything | No two jobs ever run on the same machine in parallel |

---

## 1. The collision problem and its solution

### Why collisions happen
Every local SQLite database has its own `AUTOINCREMENT` sequences starting at 1.  
Machine A has `run_id` 1–1554, Machine B will also have `run_id` 1–N.  
When both sync to PostgreSQL, `run_id=1` from Machine A collides with `run_id=1` from Machine B.

### Solution: UUID bridge (additive only)

Two new columns added to local SQLite **and** used as PK in PostgreSQL:

```
runs          → +global_run_id TEXT   (UUID, generated at row creation locally)
               +sync_status   INTEGER DEFAULT 0
experiments   → +global_exp_id TEXT   (UUID, generated at row creation locally)
child tables  → +global_run_id TEXT   (copied from runs at insert time)
```

**Local SQLite**: integer PKs remain, `global_run_id` is just an extra column.  
**PostgreSQL**: `global_run_id` IS the primary key. Integer IDs kept as reference columns.  
**All existing queries**: unchanged — they still use `run_id`, `exp_id` as before.  
**Cross-machine queries on server**: join/group on `hw_id` or `global_run_id`.

### hardware_config identity across machines

`hardware_hash` (already exists, already UNIQUE) is the stable machine fingerprint.  
On sync, the server does:
```sql
SELECT hw_id FROM hardware_config WHERE hardware_hash = $1
```
If not found → INSERT new row → get server-side `hw_id`.  
The sync payload always carries `hardware_hash`, never assumes `hw_id` is globally unique.

